3. Operative Mechanics (Theory Anchor A2)

The "First Text" (The Compiler Rules)

The poem was not pasted. It was compiled. The specific rules used to generate the JSON manifest were:

The Bellows Algorithm: Lines describing Vulcan's bellows (Lines 46-54) are mapped with a stochastic "breath" function. They occupy the center but vibrate between coordinates [11,11] and [13,13] based on the syllable count (representing intensity of the blast).

The Chiasmus of Cities: The City of Peace and City of War are perfectly mirrored.

Peace (Lines 77-108) is mapped to the "Daylight" sectors (Top Right).

War (Lines 113-150) is mapped to the "Shadow" sectors (Bottom Left).

This forces the reader to "rotate" the shield to read one or the other, preventing simultaneous focus—an operational simulation of the cognitive dissonance between war and peace.

The Ocean Constraint: The final lines describing the Ocean (Lines 259-261) are not allowed to cluster. They are exploded into individual words and forced to occupy the perimeter coordinates (x=0, x=23, y=0, y=23), effectively "binding" the grid so no other text can escape.

The "Second Text" (The Resulting Grid)

The output is a text that is no longer linear.

Sequential Reading: Impossible.

Radial Reading: You read by "drilling down" (Forge -> Out) or "scanning orbitally" (following the story of the ploughman around the ring).

